# Static Page i18n Extraction

When the user asks to "make this page translatable", "i18n'e çevir", "dil desteği ekle", or similar:

## Step 1: Extract all translatable strings

Identify every hardcoded string in the component: headings, paragraphs, button labels, alt text, aria-labels, breadcrumbs, CTA text, section titles, descriptions, list items, placeholders. Image paths and CSS classes are NOT translatable.

## Step 2: Create the data module

For a page at `src/app/(frontend)/[locale]/my-page/page.tsx` or component `src/components/MyPage.tsx`, create `src/data/my-page/`:

**en.ts** — all extracted strings with their English values:

```typescript
const en = {
  heroTitle: 'Page Title',
  heroSubtitle: 'Subtitle text',
  sections: [{ title: '...', description: '...' }],
  ctaButton: 'Contact Us',
}
export default en
```

## Step 3: Run the generator

```bash
npm run i18n:create-page my-page
```

This auto-generates `types.ts`, `index.ts`, and locale files (tr.ts, de.ts, ar.ts, etc).

## Step 4: Update the component

Replace all hardcoded strings with data from the loader:

```typescript
import { getMyPageData } from '@/data/my-page'
import { getStaticLabels } from '@/data/static-labels'

export default async function MyPage({ params }: { params: Promise<{ locale: string }> }) {
  const { locale } = await params
  const data = getMyPageData(locale)
  const labels = getStaticLabels(locale) // for shared aria/breadcrumb/product labels

  return <h1>{data.heroTitle}</h1>
}
```

## Rules

- The component MUST accept `locale` as a prop or extract it from route params
- Use `getStaticLabels(locale)` for common strings: aria-labels, breadcrumbs, product UI labels (see `src/data/static-labels/en.ts`)
- Use page-specific data loader for page content
- Keep image paths, CSS classes, and SVG icons in the component — only extract text
- Array items (like product categories) should keep their `id` field for stable keys
- After creating en.ts, ALWAYS run `npm run i18n:create-page <slug>` to generate all supporting files
- The `createLocaleLoader` in `src/data/locale-loader.ts` provides automatic EN fallback for missing locales
